Good for you for attempting baby wearing! There are lots of great tutorials to help you master the stretchy wrap. Wrapping Rachel has some great ones on YT. In case you read this before watching another tutorial:
1. Your wrap should be MUCH tighter before you put Sage in. It should fit like a snug t-shirt.
2. Babies can be legs out from birth and should be moved to the legs out position if/when they start pushing against the wrap/carrier.
3. If legs are in, it's important that baby's weight is on their bum and not their feet. Whether baby's legs are in or out you'll want to be sure that her legs form an "M" shape to keep her knees above her bum. This will position her ergonomically and protect her hips from discomfort or injury. It's also more comfortable.
4. You'll want to make sure that the fabric underneath is spread from knee to knee beginning with the part of the X that is closest to your body. The third pass (the outside fabric you pulled up) should come up to the bottom of her ears and then her shoulders as she grows.

Hang in there! With practice I'm sure you'll get it right! â¤
